	<article class="post-15930 post type-post status-publish hentry tag-argentina tag-third-world-and-developing-countries tag-ukraine des-third-world-and-developing-countries geo-argentina geo-ukraine" id="post-15930">
	<header class="postHeader">
				<div class="postKicker">
					</div>
				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Submerging Markets</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Vikas Bajaj			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-01-24T22:02:07+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">January 24, 2014 5:02 pm</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">January 24, 2014 5:02 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><div class="w480"><img src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/01/24/opinion/1242014arg/1242014arg-blog480.jpg" id="100000002669982" width="480" height="309" alt="Argentine money." /><span class="credit">Leo La Valle/Agence France-Presse â Getty Images</span><span class="caption">Argentine money.</span></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//takingnote.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/01/24/submerging-markets/" data-title="Submerging Markets" data-description="Currencies in formerly fast-growing emerging markets have been falling sharply this week.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div>Currencies in formerly fast-growing emerging markets have been <a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/01/24/a-worldwide-market-slump-gains-traction/?hp">falling sharply</a> this week. The Argentine peso and the Turkish lira, for example, were each <a href="//online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052702303448204579340480156732234?mod=WSJ_hp_LEFTTopStories">down</a> more than 1 percent against the dollar on Friday afternoon.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The market turmoil should come as no surprise to anyone who has been paying attention to the global economy in recent months. Economic growth has been slowing steadily in many developing countries and civil unrest has rocked several nations including Ukraine, Thailand and Argentina. In a column earlier this week, Ruchir Sharma, an executive at Morgan Stanley, <a href="//online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052702303465004579323153272581642">pointed out</a> that most emerging markets with the notable exception of China havenât been growing faster than the United States in the last two years, which is a big change from the previous decade when they were growing much faster.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">While each countryâs circumstances are unique, they all seem to share one thing in common: their governments are a big part of the problem.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In Argentina, for example, President Cristina FernÃ¡ndez de Kirchner has supported a policy of printing money to increase government spending. That, in turn, has driven up inflation. Independent economists <a href="//www.economist.com/news/americas/21593420-government-struggling-stay-its-feet-holding-ring?zid=305&amp;ah=417bd5664dc76da5d98af4f7a640fd8a">estimate</a> that consumer prices are rising about 25 percent a year. (The government claims inflation is much lower, but the International Monetary Fund doesnât find the countryâs official data credible.) In December, the country suffered <a href="//www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-01-23/argentine-default-era-chaos-relived-as-blackouts-follow-looting.html">mass looting</a> after police officers went on strike to protest their low pay. The country has also suffered from days-long blackouts.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In Ukraine, President Viktor F. Yanukovich recently <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/11/23/world/europe/ukraine-blames-imf-for-collapse-of-accord-with-european-union.html">rejected offers</a> of a $15 billion loan from the I.M.F. and a free-trade agreement with the European Union, which would have helped the countryâs economy, under pressure from Russia.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And in South Africa, the government of President Jacob Zuma is facing a corruption scandal even as the <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/12/10/world/africa/after-mandela-a-test-at-the-polls-for-his-party.html">unemployment</a> rate hovers around <a href="//blogs.wsj.com/economics/2014/01/05/south-african-reserve-bank-2014-outlook/">25 percent</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In the last decade, rising commodity prices and strong foreign capital flows into developing countries led many analysts to believe that these countries were sure to grow fast for years to come. That optimism lulled policy makers into a sense of complacency that they did not have to take politically difficult decisions to strengthen their economies.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But in recent months the price of commodities like gold and oil have fallen and foreign investors have begun pulling back from emerging markets in anticipation of higher interest rates in the United States. As a result, leaders of developing nations could find it much more difficult to revive their economies.</p>
	</div>
